caption: Saudi Arabian Society for Culture and Arts

name: Saudi Arabian Society for Culture and Arts
properties.summary: A governmental organization in Saudi Arabia aimed at enhancing the level of culture and arts within the country.
properties.description: The Saudi Arabian Society for Culture and Arts, established in 1973, operates under the supervision of the Ministry of Media. It was initially licensed by the General Administration for Youth Welfare under the Ministry of Labor and Social Development, now the Ministry of Human Resources and Social Development. The society began with a preliminary license and obtained its final license in 1975. Over the years, it expanded its scope to include both arts and culture, reflecting the comprehensive nature of culture itself. In 2019, culture and arts societies were incorporated into the Ministry of Culture, emphasizing their role in representing Saudi Arabia in cultural and artistic domains both regionally and internationally.
properties.keywords: Culture, Arts, Saudi Arabia, Governmental, Riyadh
properties.notes: The society has established branches across various cities in Saudi Arabi a to promote cultural and artistic activities. It also includes several committees focusing on different aspects of culture and arts, such as theater, music, and folk arts.

Throughout his life, he has faced personal tragedies including the loss of his mother and wife but has remained a significant figure in Arabic music, earning numerous awards and titles.
properties.notes: Abadi al-Johar was orphaned early in life and was raised by his mother along with his brother Abdel Rahman. He ventured into music at a young age, initially aiming for a military career before meeting Talal Maddah, which significantly changed his life's direction. Despite his personal losses, including his mother in 1974 and his wife in 2006, al-Johar continued to contribute to the world of music. He has also been a part of the Saudi Arabian Association for Culture and Arts.

description: Abdullah ibn Sulaiman Alhamdan was the first Saudi Minister of Finance, serving from 1932 to 1954. He also served as the Agent of Defence from 1933 to 1943. Born in 1884 in Unaizah, Qassim, Saudi Arabia, he was recognized for his crucial role in the financial and administrative management of the nascent state. He was instrumental in signing the first oil exploration agreement with an American company on behalf of Saudi Arabia in 1933, marking the beginning of the country's oil era. He later ventured into philanthropy, donating his palaces for educational purposes and contributing to the creation of King Abdulaziz University.
education: Studied under Saleh Al Othman Al-Qadi
title: Minister of Finance of Saudi Arabia
notes: Built the first modern hotel in Mecca, established the first school for nomads in Medina, and founded Saudi Arabia's first cement factory in Jeddah after his resignation in 1954. He passed away on November 10, 1965, in Jeddah.

properties.notes: He was the seventh son of King Saud. His educational journey began in Qatif for his primary and middle school studies, followed by his high school education in Riyadh. In 1369 AH, he went to the University of California for further studies, returning to Saudi Arabia in 1373 AH. After his return, he was appointed Vice Director of Youth Welfare by his uncle Prince Abdulmohsen bin Abdulaziz Al Saud, but he left this role shortly afterwards. His father then appointed him in the Ministry of Defense and Aviation (now the Ministry of Defense), and later he was appointed in the Ministry of Interior handling the Western Region's affairs until his retirement in 1424 AH.

properties.summary: The first Saudi Minister of Justice, served between 1971 and 1975.
properties.description: Mohammed bin Ali al Harkan was the first Minister of Justice in Saudi Arabia, serving from 1971 to 1975. Born in Medina in 1915, he grew up under the care of his father, Ali al Harkan. He received his education in Medina, initially at the only regular school at the time, which was established by Ahmad al-Fayyad Abadi, and later at the Prophetic Mosque, where he completed his studies in 1934. He started teaching at the Prophetic Mosque and also worked in commerce. He became a judge in Al-Ula by appointment from Sheikh Abdullah Al Sheikh in 1937 and moved on to become a judge in Jeddah in 1952. After serving as a judge, he was appointed the Minister of Justice with the establishment of the ministry in 1971 by King Faisal bin Abdulaziz. Post-retirement, he was nominated to work with the Muslim World League in Makkah as the Secretary General. Throughout his life, he also held several positions in educational and Islamic organizations.
properties.notes: Mohammed bin Ali al Harkan played a significant role in judicial and educational reforms in Saudi Arabia. He was involved in the dialogue between Muslim and Christian entities in the Vatican and visited Islamic minorities globally to support their causes.

description: Former Saudi Minister of Transport from 1416H to 1424H (1995AD to 2004AD). He was born in Medina in 1358H (1940AD), moved to Makkah for preliminary studies, then to Cairo for undergraduate studies, and later to the United States for his Master's and Ph.D. in Civil Engineering from the University of Arizona. Throughout his career, he held various significant positions, including General Director of Projects at the Ministry of Transport, Assistant Deputy Minister for Technical Affairs, Deputy Minister of Transport, and President of the Public Transport Company board. Additionally, he was a Vice President of the International Road Federation in Washington, a General Commissioner for Saudi Arabia's pavilions at Expo Canada and Expo USA, a member of the Development Authority of Riyadh, and a board member of Saudi Airlines. He was appointed as the Minister of Transport (the name was later changed to the Ministry of Transport), and in 1424H, he became the Secretary-General of the Makkah and Medina Development Authority.

properties.notes: He is the eighteenth son of King Saud bin Abdulaziz. He spent the first three years of his life with King Saud and his mother, but in 1946, due to his father’s preoccupations, his care was transferred to his maternal uncle's house, where he was raised until 1963. After finishing his bachelor's degree in the UK in 1967, he moved to Greece to meet his father. His father died in 1968, and he had lived with his father for only five years and his mother for 23 years. He returned to the Kingdom only for his father's funeral in 1968 and then went to Greece again. Convinced by his brother, Prince Abdul Ilah bin Saud, he returned to the Kingdom in 1975 and has been in his position at Al-Nassr Football Club for over 35 years.

name: Jamil Ibrahim Hejailan

properties.notes: Jamil Ibrahim Hejailan was born in Deir ez-Zor, northeast Syria, into a family of the 'Aqilat' that had migrated from Najd to the Levant. His father, Sheikh Ibrahim Al-Hejailan, was a prominent trader of the 'Aqilat'. To ensure the memory of Buraidah, the family's ancestral home, remained alive in his son's memory, he was registered as born in Buraidah at the Saudi Consulate in Damascus when Hejailan was ten years old. Hejailan attended Quranic school at age six, followed by primary education at Abdul Rahman Al-Ghafiqi school and then preparatory school, with prominent teacher Sheikh Ali Al-Tantawi teaching him language and literature. In 1944, he moved to Cairo for secondary and university education, earning a law degree from Cairo University in 1950.

He also serves as Chairman of the Board of Directors for Saudi Arabian Airlines and the Saudi Railways Company (SAR). With 30 years of experience in business management, maritime, land, and air transport, and significant involvement in both the private and public sectors, Al-Jasser has held several executive positions including General Manager of Saudi Arabian Airlines and CEO of the National Shipping Company of Saudi Arabia (Bahri). He has also been involved in leadership roles at major institutions such as the Industrial Development Fund.
notes: Al-Jasser received King Abdulaziz Sash of the second class from King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud on April 6, 2021. He has various memberships in executive boards, including the Saudi Football Union, Saudi Civil Aviation Holding Company, and others until July 2014.

properties.notes: Faisal Al-Hegelan served as a Saudi diplomat and politician. Born in Jeddah in 1929 to a family from Buraidah, Qassim region. He graduated with a Bachelor of Laws from Fuad I University in Cairo in 1951 after attending The Missions School in Mecca. Starting his diplomatic career in 1952, he held various diplomatic positions around the world, including in Washington, Madrid, Buenos Aires, Caracas, London, and Copenhagen. Al-Hegelan became the Saudi Ambassador to the United States in 1979 and held the position until 1983. He later served as the Minister of Health from 1985 to 1995 and was involved in various humanitarian and health-related roles until his death in 2019.

description: Tunisian Islamic leader, Mufti of the Republic of Tunisia from 1984 to 1998
position: Mufti of the Republic of Tunisia
notes: Received a certificate of achievement in religious sciences from Zitouna University, followed by a global certificate in the branch of the fundamentals of religion from the same university. He then began teaching at the university, before joining the Higher Institute of the Basics of Religion in Tunisia to study in the specialization of Quranic studies, jurisprudence, and legislation rules.
Member of the International Islamic Fiqh Academy in Jeddah, and the Head of the Global Shariah Authority for Zakat.

Presided over the Islamic Supreme Council in Tunisia between 1989 and 1993, and was also the Head of the Shariah Board at Al Baraka Bank in its Tunisia branch. Member of the Shariah Compliance Body in Bahrain, and currently a member of the Shariah Body of Zitouna Bank in Tunisia.

Author of numerous works including 'Zaitouna Education and Means of its Reform', 'The Family and the Society', 'Ijtihad and Renewal', 'Islamic Guidance', 'Horizons of Research in the Science of Maqasid', 'Ijtihad: The Text, The Reality, The Interest', 'Research in the Purposes of Sharia: Its Emergence, Development, and Future', and more.

Awarded the Higher Class of the Order of the Republic of Tunisia, the Cultural Badge of the Republic of Tunisia, the Seventh of November Order, the Medal of Excellence from the first class. Received an award from the Kuwait Foundation for the Advancement of Sciences and the Islamic Organization for Medical Sciences in 2001, and an award from the Islamic Development Bank in the field of Islamic banking and finance in 2007.

name: General Intelligence Presidency

properties.summary: The General Intelligence Presidency (GIP) is the primary intelligence agency of Saudi Arabia. It is one of the main security institutions in the Kingdom, focused primarily on providing security and stability by gathering intelligence within the kingdom and abroad.
properties.description: Founded in 1955 under the name of Al-Mabahith Al-Aammah by King Saud bin Abdulaziz Al Saud, the General Intelligence Presidency has evolved into one of Saudi Arabia's most significant security agencies. It works in close collaboration with other security bodies to safeguard national achievements and citizen's well-being both inside and outside the Kingdom. With a well-defined administrative structure, the presidency carries out strategic intelligence operations that contribute to the country's national security. Historical involvement includes the use of intelligence in battles for unification, and the establishment of the first wireless communications network across the country, significantly enhancing information relay and strategic planning capabilities.
properties.keywords: Intelligence, Security, Saudi Arabia, National Security, GIP, Estikhabarat
properties.notes: The GIP has been involved in various operations domestically and internationally, aiming to counter threats and maintain stability. It has undergone several phases of development, expanding its capabilities and reach.

description: Yousef Bin Yaqoub Al Hairi, born in 1910, was a foundational figure in Saudi healthcare, serving as the Minister of Health from 1962 to 1966. Part of the first Saudi educational mission to Egypt in the 1920s, he was among the top ten students in Egypt and went on to graduate from King Fouad University's Faculty of Medicine. Alongside Dr. Hamad Al Basam, he became one of the first Saudi physicians from the central region. Al Hairi, who passed away in 1975, is remembered for his commitment to honesty and simplicity.

properties.summary: One of the key branches of the Saudi military forces, acting as a sovereign and supportive ministry to the Saudi Army, equipped with comprehensive gear and occasionally working alongside the land forces.
properties.description: The Saudi Arabian National Guard (SANG) is an important branch of the Saudi military forces, operating both as a sovereign and supportive ministry to the Saudi Army. It is equipped with comprehensive military gear and plays a crucial role in supporting the Royal Guard, the internal security forces during internal security instability, and combating terrorism and terrorist organizations. Established in 1917, SANG performs a variety of roles including defense of the Kingdom's territory and borders, maintaining internal security and stability, and protecting state sanctities and accomplishments.

properties.title: Queen
properties.summary: Iffat Al-Thunayan, also known as Iffat bint Mohammad Al Thunayan, was a significant figure in Saudi Arabian history, known for her role as an education activist, and as the wife of King Faisal bin Abdulaziz Al Saud. Born in Istanbul in 1916 to a princely branch of the Al Saud family that had moved to Turkey, Iffat played a pioneering role in the field of female education in Saudi Arabia, founding the Dar Al-Hanan School, the first school for girls in the country, and Iffat University in Jeddah. She was also instrumental in the establishment of the King Faisal Specialist Hospital and Research Centre in Riyadh. She passed away on February 17, 2000, in Riyadh following surgery at the age of 84.
properties.position: Queen of Saudi Arabia, Politician
properties.notes: Iffat Al Thunayan is recognized for her significant contributions to education and healthcare in Saudi Arabia. She is remembered for her support of social and cultural dialogues through her engagements with women from various social backgrounds and for her role in the establishment of meaningful educational and healthcare institutions. She was the first wife named as queen in the history of the kingdom.

properties.additionalInformation: Suffered from colon cancer and passed away in New York, where he had been receiving treatment. His health had been deteriorating in the years prior to his death, which led him to spend extended periods outside Saudi Arabia for medical care. He was buried in Al Oud Cemetery, Riyadh, next to King Fahd bin Abdulaziz.

properties.summary: Alanoud Al-Fayez, born in 1957, is the former wife of King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia. She is a member of the Fayez tribe from Bani Sakhr. She had four daughters with King Abdullah and has been living in London since her divorce in 2003.
properties.notes: One of her daughters, Princess Hala, passed away on September 30, 2021. Alanoud Al-Fayez sought international help, including from Barack Obama and the United Nations, to free her four daughters, who were detained by their father for 14 years.

Al Jawhara also encouraged the practice of horseback riding among young princes, recognizing its importance in combination with education and strength.

properties.summary: Sultan bin Salman Al Saud, born on June 27, 1956, in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, is the second son of King Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud. He is recognized as the first Arab and first Muslim astronaut, part of the STS-51-G mission in 1985. With a military rank of Colonel in the Royal Saudi Air Force, he also served as the chief executive officer of the Saudi Space Commission until May 2, 2021, and holds a ministerial rank as a special advisor to the Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques since then. Sultan has significant involvement in tourism, aviation, and heritage through various leadership positions.

properties.description: Asaad Abdul Aziz Alzuhair was a Saudi military pilot who graduated with the rank of Second lieutenant after several years of study in London. He was appointed as the commander of the Saudi Aviation Weapon (1963-1966) and commander of the Saudi Royal Air Forces (1972-1979). name: Mohammed
properties.summary: Mohammed is a male Arabic name meaning 'praised, commendable'. It is especially revered among Muslims due to its association with Prophet Muhammad, leading to its widespread popularity in the Islamic world. The name has also seen significant use in various countries and is known for its numerous derivatives and variations across different languages.
properties.description: The name Mohammed originates from the Arabic linguistic root H-M-D, meaning praise, commendation, and glorification. Its variations, including Ahmad, Mahmoud, and others, derive from the same root. Historically, the name did not appear extensively until shortly before the advent of Islam, gaining popularity with the prophecy of Prophet Muhammad's coming, leading some Arabs to name their children Mohammed in hope and anticipation. The name Mohammed is directly linked to Prophet Muhammad, making it highly regarded among Muslims and resulting in its widespread use. It is considered a tradition to name children Mohammed, though the Prophet's kunya, Abul Qasim, is not used for this purpose. The name's popularity transcends cultural and national boundaries, seeing varied spelling and pronunciation across different languages. Notable historical figures, rulers, artists, athletes, and more have carried the name Mohammed, further embedding it into the cultural and religious identity of numerous communities.
properties.keywords: Islamic, Prophet Muhammad, Popular, Arabic name, Praised
properties.notes: The usage of the name Mohammed has seen a notable increase in various regions, including the UK and France, over the years. In Britain, the use of the name increased by 83% among newborns from 2000 to 2011, becoming the third most popular name according to the National Statistics Office. Similar trends have been observed in France, especially after the construction of the Grand Mosque of Paris in 1926. Moreover, the Chechen authorities encouraged the naming of newborn boys as Mohammed on the Prophet's birth date in 2009, with incentives provided to the families. The name's spelling and pronunciation vary across different cultures and languages, reflecting its global acceptance and reverence.

properties.summary: Abd al-Rahman al-Ashmawi is a Saudi poet and university professor known for his Islamic poetry. Born in ʻAraʻ, al-Bāḥah in 1956 to a Syrian father and a Saudi mother, he pursued his education in Arabic Language at Imam Muhammad ibn Saud Islamic University, where he earned his bachelor's, master's, and Ph.D. degrees. Ashmawi is renowned for his poems that address the tribulations of Muslims worldwide and has published numerous articles and poetry anthologies. He has also participated in various literary seminars and media programs.

properties.fatherName: A Syrian man from Tell Shihab, Hauran, Southern Syria

name: Ministry of Defense Saudi Arabia
properties.Person:description: The Ministry of Defense is one of the sovereign ministries in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia charged with the administrative, operational, and logistical affairs directly related to national security and the armed forces. Its responsibility includes defending the Kingdom's territories and interests against external threats. The ministry comprises four main branches which are the land forces, naval forces, air forces, and air defense forces, along with several affiliated entities including the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the military intelligence agency, and the national defense center.
Person:alias: Ministry of Defense and Aviation and General Inspection
Ministry of Defense and General Inspection
properties.Person:notes: The Ministry of Defense plays a significant role in implementing Saudi Vision 2030 with strategic objectives such as achieving operational excellence, developing organizational performance, individual performance enhancement, spending efficiency, supporting military manufacturing localization, and modernizing equipment and weapons. The ministry's budget for military spending in 2022 was 171 billion Saudi Riyals, a decrease of 10.2% from the previous year's spending.

properties.summary: Khalid bin Abdulaziz Al Saud was the fourth king of Saudi Arabia, ruling from March 25, 1975, until his death on June 13, 1982. He succeeded King Faisal and was succeeded by King Fahd. His reign saw the development of Saudi Arabia's infrastructure and the promotion of the nation as a leading oil producer. King Khalid's era was marked by economic prosperity due to high oil revenues, as well as significant contributions to the modernization of the kingdom and expansion of the two Holy Mosques. He also played a key role in foreign affairs, fostering relationships with both Western and Islamic countries.

position: Governor of Tabuk Region
properties.notes: Was appointed as the Governor of Tabuk Region in 1986 until 1987. Afterward, he was appointed as the head of the Center for Strategic Studies, a position he held until he requested exemption. Obtained a Master's degree in History from King Abdulaziz University in Jeddah in 1983, and a PhD in International Studies from the University of Alexandria. Known for his religious interests and was the honorary president of the Quranic Studies Institute for Girls in Mecca. Criticized the Muslim Brotherhood and defended the Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice, and Salafi call. He had several writings that attack and advise a number of scholars and writers in Saudi Arabia and abroad.
